node.text:
Beautiful rainbow cloud phenomenon at Merritt Island in Florida 🌈😍

Have you ever seen phenomenon such as this?
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Iridescence (also known as goniochromism) is the phenomenon of certain surfaces that appear to gradually change color as the angle of view or the angle of illumination changes.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ 
Iridescent Clouds are also referred to as “fire rainbows” or “rainbow clouds”. The scientific name is circumhorizontal arcs, which is an optical phenomenon that belongs to the family of ice halos formed by the refraction of sunlight or moonlight in plate-shaped ice crystals suspended in the atmosphere, typically in cirrus or cirrostratus clouds. They occur when the sun is higher than 58° above the horizon. The light of the sun passes through high-altitude cirrus clouds (short, detached, hair-like clouds found at high altitudes) that are made up of hexagonal plate ice crystals. When they align perfectly, the ice crystals act just like a prism. This results in the refraction of the light which gives the look of a rainbow in the clouds.

🎥: Christian Servant Patriot

node.text:
The night the moon dressed like Saturn⁣⁣ 🪐 

How would you best caption this capture?

⁣⁣From afar you may wonder, “Is that an asteroid ring around the moon?”. Well, the disguise of this waning moon is actually a thin cirrostratus cloud. The way the cloud interacts with the moon creates a unique display of beauty that steals protagonism from the surrounding stars. Below the moon? The dimly lit silhouette of volcano Pacaya and the Guatemalan highlands can be appreciated.⁣⁣

⁣⁣⁣Captured at dawn December 24, 2019⁣
⁣⁣
📸 @francisco_sojuel

node.text:
Rings in Jupiter?! 😨

If until today you thought that only Saturn has rings... you have been mistaken all your life. 😬 The other gas planets (Jupiter, Uranus and Neptune) also have rings. However, they are very faint and extremely difficult to observe, unlike Saturn, which with virtually any telescope, you can see them.

Jupiter's thin rings are made of ice and rocky materials, but mostly dust. They were first observed by the Voyager 1 spacecraft in 1979. After that, they were seen again that same year by Voyager 2 and lastly, they were studied by the Galileo spacecraft, which was a spacecraft designed to study Jupiter in particular.

The New Horizons probe, which was sent to Pluto, passed by Jupiter and can also see them, bringing some important information about the structure of the rings.

Here on Earth they can also be visible. But not by amateur telescopes, but by the biggest telescopes in the world. The Hubble Space Telescope has seen them too.

node.text:
The planet Mercury 🔭🌌

This is one of the closest images of the surface of the planet Mercury. This image was taken by NASA’s Messenger Spacecraft, the spacecraft was really close when it took this image. Mercury is the smallest planet in the Solar System and the closest to the Sun. Its orbit around the Sun takes 87.97 Earth days, the shortest of all the Sun's planets.

What’s your favorite planet? I love Saturn 🪐❤️

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Space Spot Astronomy & Science on September 11, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'NASA astronaut Frank Culbertson was the only American not on the planet when the 9/11 terrorist attacks occurred. This is one of the photos he took. His morning call started with Mission Control telling him "Frank, we're not having a very good day down here on Earth"'.

node.text:
On this day, 20 years ago 💔

At the time, the astronauts did not have live TV or Internet at the space station. But Culbertson saw on the astronauts' map that the orbiting outpost was over southern Canada and about to pass over New England. 

He grabbed a camera and moved to a window in the Russian portion of the space station, where he had a clear view of the dark smoke over New York.

node.text:
Stunning footage of sharks swimming through a school of fish🐟🦈

This was shot in the Hamptons, a group of towns, villages, and hamlets nestled on the eastern end of Long Island in New York state. It's a popular destination for New York City dwellers, especially during the summertime.

Follow @Spacespot for more wonders ✨

🎥: @southforksalt

node.text:
The violent center of the Carina Nebula, a 460 light year wide monster holding some of the most beautiful gas and dust structures in the Milky Way for our eyes to see! 🔭

Follow @Spacespot to explore the Universe 🚀
⠀
At the center, the Mystic Mountain region is three light years in height and contains nascent stars which fire off jets of gas which can be seen streaming from the mountain peaks. The gas pillar is being slowly eroded by the light of the enormously large, massive young stars located above the pillar. ✨

Tag a friend that loves space 🤩

📸: NASA/ HUBBLE TELESCOPE
